[[!meta title="Check the file system of the persistent volume"]]

In rare occasions, you might have to perform a file system check to repair a
broken persistent volume.

Mount the encrypted volume
==========================

1. Start Tails, with persistence disabled, and [[set up an administration
   password|startup_options/administration_password]].

1. Choose
   <span class="menuchoice">
     <span class="guimenu">Applications</span>&nbsp;▸
     <span class="guisubmenu">Utilities</span>&nbsp;▸
     <span class="guimenuitem">Disks</span>
   </span>
   to open <span class="application">GNOME Disks</span>.

1. In the left pane, click on the device corresponding to your Tails device.

1. In the right pane, click on the partition labeled as
   <span class="guilabel">LUKS</span>. The
   <span class="guilabel">Partition Label</span> must be
   <span class="label">TailsData</span>.

1. Click on <span class="guimenu">[[!img lib/unlock.png alt="Unlock device" class=symbolic link=no]]</span>
   to unlock the old persistent volume. Enter the passphrase of the old persistent
   volume and click <span class="guilabel">Unlock</span>.

1. In the confirmation dialog, enter your administration password and click
   <span class="guilabel">Authenticate</span>.

1. Click on the <span class="guilabel">TailsData</span> partition that
   appears below the <span class="guilabel">Encrypted Volume</span>
   partition. The name of the device will appear below the layout of the volumes.

Check the filesystem using the terminal
=======================================

1. Choose
    <span class="menuchoice">
      <span class="guimenu">Applications</span>&nbsp;▸
      <span class="guisubmenu">System Tools</span>&nbsp;▸
      <span class="guimenuitem">Root Terminal</span></span>
   and then type the administration password you set up before in the confirmation
   dialog, to open a root terminal.

1. In the terminal window, type <span class="command">fsck -y /dev/mapper/luks-name-of-your-device</span>
   to start the check of the filesystem. The name of your device is the name
   <span class="application">GNOME Disks</span> displayed previously.
   You can complete the name of it
   by typing <span class="command">fsck -y /dev/mapper/luks</span>
   and pressing `TAB`.

1. The filesystem is without errors when the last line from the output of the 
   command starts with <span class="command">TailsData: clean</span>.

